ogy, linguistics, and forensic science to produce a scathing critique of "Prevention through Deterrence," the federal border enforcement policy that encourages migrants to cross in areas characterized by extreme environmental conditions and high risk of death. For two decades, this policy has failed to deter border crossers while successfully turning the rugged terrain of southern Arizona into a killing field. In harrowing detail, De León chronicles the journeys of people who have made dozens of attempts to cross the border and uncovers the stories of the objects and bodies left behind in the desert.The Land of Open Graves will spark debate and controversy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aBorder securityxSocial aspectsxArizona. 0aBorder securityxSocial aspectsxMexican-American Border Region. 0aBorder securityxSocial aspectszArizona. 0aBorder securityxSocial aspectszMexican-American Border Region. 0aImmigration enforcementxSocial aspectsxArizona. 0aImmigration enforcementxSocial aspectsxMexican-American Border Region. 0aImmigration enforcementxSocial aspectszArizona. 0aImmigration enforcementxSocial aspectszMexican-American Border Region. 4aanthropologist. 4aanthropology. 4acoyotes. 4adangers of border crossing. 4aenvironmental extremes. 4aethnographer. 4aimmigrant studies. 4aimmigration policy. 4amexico-united states border. 4apolitical activism. 4arisk of death. 4asociologist. 4asonoran desert of arizona. 4aundocumented migrants. 4aus immigration policy. 4aus politics. 4awhat its like to cross the border. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311062111208iTit